            <specpara>
                <important>
                    <para>At the assembly plant, all the DIP switches are set at 0, and the speedometer and tachometer
                        are programmed electronically through the Data Link. The speedometer and tachometer receive the
                        proper setting, but the switch levers remain on 0. Moving any of the DIP switches from the 0
                        position disables the speedometer and tachometer programming.
                        <emph type="boldital">If a DIP switch is moved for re-programming or any other reason, then all
                            the DIP switches must be moved to the positions indicated on the vehicle's line set ticket.
                        </emph>
                        This information may also be found on a label,
                        <hotlnk xrefid="f0803415">Figure 15</hotlnk>, affixed to the top of the cluster. If all the
                        switches are returned to 0, the original factory programmed settings will be re-enabled.
                    </para>
                </important>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="f0803415" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g0803415" filename="../figg08/G0803415.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Dip Switch Settings Label</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <important>
                    <para>Beginning in 1994, some vehicles with electronically controlled engines may receive
                        speedometer and tachometer input via the data link rather than directly from flywheel and
                        transmission mounted sensors. In that case, there may be no flywheel sensor. The electronically
                        controlled engine will still need a transmission mounted sensor.
                    </para>
                </important>
            </specpara>
